    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>CHINA EASES RESTRICTIONS ON SURVEYS</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By Craig S. Smith</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Smith, Craig S</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Chinese Government rescinds restrictions on poll taking in country, saying foreigners can order surveys without having first to submit their questionnaires for government approval, as long as surveys avoid politically related topics; easing of restrictions is break for foreign companies seeking market research on China's consumers; survey results no longer have to be reported to government (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>In a break for foreign companies seeking market research on China's consumers, the government rescinded restrictions on poll taking in the country, saying foreigners can order surveys without having first to submit their questionnaires for government approval, as long as the surveys avoid politically related topics. Survey results no longer have to be reported to the government, China's National Bureau of Statistics said.</p>
        <p>Craig S. Smith (NYT)</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>In a break for foreign companies seeking market research on China's consumers, the government rescinded restrictions on poll taking in the country, saying foreigners can order surveys without having first to submit their questionnaires for government approval, as long as the surveys avoid politically related topics. Survey results no longer have to be reported to the government, China's National Bureau of Statistics said.</p>
        <p>Craig S. Smith (NYT)</p>
